Here is a solution using a simple linear search algorithm to sort the array in ascending order and return it in O(n) time complexity:

1. Initialize a counter variable i to 0.
2. While the array has more than 1 element:
3.   Compare the element at index i with the element at index (i+1)%nums.length.
4.   If the element at index i is less than the element at index (i+1)%nums.length, then swap their positions.
5.   Increment i.
6.   Repeat step 2 until the array is sorted.

Here is the pseudocode for the above algorithm:

```
function sortArrayInAscendingOrder(nums)
{  
    int i;
    int j;
    int tmp;

    // Initialize counter variable i to 0
    i = 0;

    // While the array has more than 1 element
    while(nums.length > 1)
    {
        // Compare the element at index i with the element at index (i+1)%nums.length.
        j = (i+1)%nums.length;
        if(nums[i] < nums[j])
        {
            // Swap their positions.
            tmp = nums[i];
            nums[i] = nums[j];
            nums[j] = tmp;
        }
        // Increment i.
        i++;
    }

    // Return the sorted array.
    return nums;
}
```

Note that, for an array of size n, the above algorithm runs in O(n) time complexity. It also uses only one bit of extra space to store the counter variable i.

